      • toString

        public java.lang.String toString()
        Returns a string representation of the container. The string representation consists of a list of the container's elements, enclosed in square brackets ("[]"). Adjacent elements are separated by the characters ", " (comma and space). Example: 
             Container container = new Container();
     container.add("A");
     container.add("B");
     System.out.println(container); // Outputs: [A, B]
        Overrides:

      • equals

        public boolean equals​(java.lang.Object obj)
        Compares the specified object with this container for equality. Returns true if and only if the specified object is also a container, both containers have the same size, and all corresponding pairs of elements in the two containers are equal. Two containers are considered equal if they have the same elements in the same order.
        Overrides:
        equals in class java.lang.Object
        Parameters:
        obj - the object to be compared for equality with this container
        Returns:
        true if the specified object is equal to this container, false otherwise

      • hashCode

        public int hashCode()
        Returns the hash code value for this container. The hash code of a container is defined as the sum of the hash codes of its elements, where the hash code of a null element is defined to be 0. The formula used for calculating the hash code is: 
             int hashCode = 1;
     for (Object element : container) {
         hashCode = 31 * hashCode + (element == null ? 0 : element.hashCode());
     }
        This ensures that container1.equals(container2) implies that container1.hashCode() == container2.hashCode().
        Overrides:
        hashCode in class java.lang.Object
        Returns:
        the hash code value for this container

      • iterator

        public java.util.Iterator<java.lang.Object> iterator()
        Returns an iterator over the elements in this container in proper sequence. The returned iterator will iterate over the elements in the order in which they were added to the container. Example usage: 
             Container container = new Container();
     container.add("A");
     container.add("B");
     for (Object item : container) {
         System.out.println(item); // Outputs: A, B
     }
        Specified by:
        iterator in interface java.lang.Iterable<java.lang.Object>

        an iterator over the elements in this container
